<P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#dcdeed><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bnamelesstavern.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=doranashae>Dorana Shae</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Registered User</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#333333>10/3/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#333333>8:44:18 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: a Sincere Thank you. To ... </font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">What an awesome idea for a thread. Gotta add my own...<br>
<br>
Lenardo... many moons ago I was a 5th level newbie hunting pumas in the East Commonlands and you saved my tail when I got outnumbered and bandaged me back from bleeding to death. We chatted for a few minutes and you inspected me and gave me a pair of drake-hide leggings. I thought I'd just found the pot of gold at the end of the rainbow! I was still very new to Norrath at that point and your kindness shaped the way I play to this day. I passed those leggings on to a young monk when I no longer needed them, and I know he passed them on to another deserving newbie. <br>
<br>
Tstorm... I recall the time when I was hunting zombies in the EC ruins and you were hunting guards. Unlike many who hunted the guards, you took it upon yourself to replace them for as long as you hunted there and encouraged newbies to run to you for help. I remember watching in awe (hey, I was 9th level) as you decimated countless ghoul trains, grinning as you went. I remember once you wandered into the ruins to face four ghouls with less than half a bubble of health left in your bar. To this day, I can never resist an opportunity to decimate those same ghoul trains when newbies have need.<br>
<br>
Vaelie... my sister (yeah, yeah, don't get technical, I know ;-) I remember hunting with you and your friends in Cazic-Thule and learning that nothing was impossible if you were determined enough. I still don't know how we survived some of those fights, but the fact remains that we did, and we did things that shouldn't have been possible at our level. Though you may not be a singer yourself, you taught me the confidence that makes a bard great.<br>
<br>
There are many more I could add. The dark elves who watched me die one day when I took on something that was too tough for me, thus teaching me both caution and respect for different beliefs. The monk who saw me losing an attempt to solo a griffene and gave it a flying kick or two in passing thus ensuring I got my first lambent bracer. The many clerics who have seen my sorry corpse lying somewhere and have called it back to life and guarded me while I dressed. The many high level players whose deeds have inspired my songs. The many dear companions I wander with from day to day. Such actions are never forgotten, such kindnesses are always returned.<br>
<br>
Waes hael to all. The bard remembers.<br>
<br>
Dorana Shae<br>
